# 15: BPE Tokenization — From a 1994 Compression Hack to the Heart of Every LLM

```elixir
Code.require_file("setup.exs", __DIR__)

Mix.install([
  {:ex_nano_gpt, path: "."},
  {:vega_lite, "~> 0.1"},
  {:kino_vega_lite, "~> 0.1"},
  {:kino, "~> 0.14"}
])

NotebookSetup.configure_backend!()
alias VegaLite, as: Vl
```

## Tokenize Your Name

Type your name below. Our v1 character-level model treats every byte as one token. How expensive is that?

```elixir
name_input = Kino.Input.text("Your name")
```

```elixir
name = Kino.Input.read(name_input)
bytes = :binary.bin_to_list(name)

IO.puts("\"#{name}\" = #{length(bytes)} bytes = #{length(bytes)} tokens")
IO.puts("Bytes: #{inspect(bytes)}")
IO.puts("As chars: #{inspect(Enum.map(bytes, &<<&1>>))}")
IO.puts("\nEvery single character is a separate token.")
IO.puts("The word 'the' costs 3 tokens. Every. Single. Time.")
```

Now think about this: in the complete works of Shakespeare (~1MB), the word " the" (with a leading space) appears about 23,000 times. That's 92,000 tokens for one word. Shouldn't "the" just be... one token?

In February 1994, a programmer named **Philip Gage** published a short article in the *C Users Journal* — a hobbyist magazine for C programmers. His algorithm was called **Byte Pair Encoding**: find the most common pair of bytes, replace them with a new symbol, repeat. It was a simple data compression trick.

Twenty-two years later, in 2016, **Rico Sennrich** (yes — the same Sennrich who co-authored RMSNorm in 2019) and colleagues at the University of Edinburgh realized this compression algorithm could solve the "open vocabulary" problem in machine translation. Before BPE, models had fixed vocabularies and choked on new words. After BPE, any text could be represented as a sequence of subword tokens.

Today, GPT-4 uses ~100,000 BPE tokens. Every modern LLM uses some variant of BPE. Let's build it from scratch.

## Math Notation

BPE is pure string manipulation -- no tensors needed. But it still has a key equation:

| Formula | Meaning | Elixir | Nx |
|---------|---------|--------|----|
| `V` | Vocabulary (set of all tokens) | `MapSet.new(0..255)` | N/A (preprocessing) |
| `\|V\|` | Vocabulary size | `MapSet.size(vocab)` | N/A |
| `f(p, q)` | Frequency of adjacent pair | `Enum.frequencies(pairs)` | N/A |
| `(p*, q*) = argmax f(p,q)` | Find the most frequent pair | `Enum.max_by(freqs, fn {_k,v} -> v end)` | N/A |

<details>
<summary>All symbols so far (notebooks 00-15)</summary>

| Symbol | Meaning | First seen |
|--------|---------|-----------|
| `Σ`, `xᵢ`, `n`, `W ∈ ℝ`, `W[i]` | Basics | 00-01 |
| `μ, σ², ε, γ, β` | Normalization | 02 |
| `Q, K, V, d_k, softmax, ^T` | Attention | 03 |
| `GELU, Φ, erf` | Activation | 05 |
| `x + F(x)`, `W_E^T` | Residuals, weight tying | 06-07 |
| `L, log, P(y\|x)` | Loss | 08 |
| `α, β₁/β₂, ∇, θ, λ, ∇_θ L` | Optimization | 09-10 |
| `T` | Temperature | 12 |
| `V, \|V\|, f(p,q), argmax` | BPE tokenization | 15 |

</details>

## See the Pairs

Let's look at what happens when we scan text for adjacent byte pairs:

```elixir
text = "the cat sat on the mat"
bytes = :binary.bin_to_list(text)
IO.puts("\"#{text}\" = #{length(bytes)} byte-tokens\n")

pairs =
  bytes
  |> Enum.chunk_every(2, 1, :discard)
  |> Enum.frequencies()
  |> Enum.sort_by(fn {_, c} -> -c end)
  |> Enum.take(5)

IO.puts("Top 5 adjacent byte pairs:")

for {{a, b}, count} <- pairs do
  a_s = if a in 32..126, do: <<a>>, else: "0x#{Integer.to_string(a, 16)}"
  b_s = if b in 32..126, do: <<b>>, else: "0x#{Integer.to_string(b, 16)}"
  IO.puts("  (#{a}, #{b}) = '#{a_s}#{b_s}'  x#{count}")
end

IO.puts("\nBPE would merge the most frequent pair first, creating a new token.")
```

## Build BPE from Scratch

### Step 1: Count Byte-Pair Frequencies

```elixir
count_pairs = fn ids ->
  # TODO:
  # 1. Enum.chunk_every(ids, 2, 1, :discard) to get [a, b] pairs
  # 2. Enum.reduce into a map: %{ {a, b} => count, ... }
  %{}
end

test_ids = [104, 101, 108, 108, 111, 104, 101]
counts = count_pairs.(test_ids)
IO.inspect(counts, label: "pair counts")
IO.puts("Pair {104, 101} ('h','e') should appear 2 times: #{Map.get(counts, {104, 101}, 0)}")
```

<details>
<summary>Solution</summary>

```elixir
count_pairs = fn ids ->
  ids
  |> Enum.chunk_every(2, 1, :discard)
  |> Enum.reduce(%{}, fn [a, b], acc ->
    Map.update(acc, {a, b}, 1, &(&1 + 1))
  end)
end
```

</details>

### Step 2: The Merge Operation

Replace every occurrence of a pair `{p1, p2}` with a new token ID. Pattern matching on list heads makes this natural in Elixir.

```elixir
defmodule BPE do
  def merge(ids, {p1, p2}, new_id) do
    # TODO: implement using do_merge(ids, p1, p2, new_id, [])
    #
    # Base cases:
    #   do_merge([], ..., acc) -> Enum.reverse(acc)
    #   do_merge([a], ..., acc) -> Enum.reverse([a | acc])
    #
    # Match: when a == p1 and b == p2 ->
    #   do_merge(rest, ..., [new_id | acc])
    #
    # No match:
    #   do_merge([b | rest], ..., [a | acc])
    ids
  end
end

IO.puts("merge([1,2,3,1,2,4], {1,2}, 256)")
IO.puts("Expected: [256, 3, 256, 4]")
IO.puts("Got:      #{inspect(BPE.merge([1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 4], {1, 2}, 256))}")

IO.puts("\nmerge([2,2,2], {2,2}, 256)  (greedy left-to-right)")
IO.puts("Expected: [256, 2]")
IO.puts("Got:      #{inspect(BPE.merge([2, 2, 2], {2, 2}, 256))}")
```

<details>
<summary>Solution</summary>

```elixir
defmodule BPE do
  def merge(ids, {p1, p2}, new_id), do: do_merge(ids, p1, p2, new_id, [])

  defp do_merge([], _, _, _, acc), do: Enum.reverse(acc)
  defp do_merge([a], _, _, _, acc), do: Enum.reverse([a | acc])

  defp do_merge([a, b | rest], p1, p2, new_id, acc) when a == p1 and b == p2 do
    do_merge(rest, p1, p2, new_id, [new_id | acc])
  end

  defp do_merge([a | rest], p1, p2, new_id, acc) do
    do_merge(rest, p1, p2, new_id, [a | acc])
  end
end
```

</details>

### Step 3: Train — Watch Merges Happen

Now combine counting and merging into a training loop. Each iteration finds the most frequent pair and creates a new token.

```elixir
training_text = "the cat sat on the mat. the cat ate the rat. the fat cat and the hat."
ids = :binary.bin_to_list(training_text)
IO.puts("Training text (#{byte_size(training_text)} bytes):\n  \"#{training_text}\"\n")

num_merges = 20

{merges, final_ids, _next_id} =
  Enum.reduce(1..num_merges, {[], ids, 256}, fn step, {merges, ids, next_id} ->
    counts = count_pairs.(ids)

    if map_size(counts) == 0 do
      {merges, ids, next_id}
    else
      {{p1, p2} = best_pair, freq} = Enum.max_by(counts, fn {_, c} -> c end)
      new_ids = BPE.merge(ids, best_pair, next_id)

      p1_s = if p1 in 32..126, do: <<p1>>, else: "#{p1}"
      p2_s = if p2 in 32..126, do: <<p2>>, else: "#{p2}"

      IO.puts(
        "Merge #{String.pad_leading("#{step}", 2)}: " <>
          "'#{p1_s}'+'#{p2_s}' -> #{next_id}  " <>
          "freq=#{freq}  tokens: #{length(ids)} -> #{length(new_ids)}"
      )

      {[{best_pair, next_id} | merges], new_ids, next_id + 1}
    end
  end)

merges = Enum.reverse(merges)
IO.puts("\n#{byte_size(training_text)} bytes -> #{length(final_ids)} tokens")
IO.puts("Compression: #{Float.round(byte_size(training_text) / max(length(final_ids), 1), 2)}x")
```

Watch how "t"+"h" merge first, then " "+"t" (space+t), building up to common words. This is BPE discovering the structure of English, one merge at a time.

### Visualize: Compression Over Merges

```elixir
ids = :binary.bin_to_list(training_text)
original_len = length(ids)

{ratio_data, _, _} =
  Enum.reduce(0..num_merges, {[], ids, 256}, fn
    0, {data, ids, next_id} ->
      {[%{"merges" => 0, "tokens" => original_len, "ratio" => 1.0} | data], ids, next_id}

    _step, {data, ids, next_id} ->
      counts = count_pairs.(ids)

      if map_size(counts) == 0 do
        {data, ids, next_id}
      else
        {best_pair, _} = Enum.max_by(counts, fn {_, c} -> c end)
        new_ids = BPE.merge(ids, best_pair, next_id)
        ratio = Float.round(original_len / length(new_ids), 3)
        step_num = next_id - 256 + 1

        entry = %{"merges" => step_num, "tokens" => length(new_ids), "ratio" => ratio}
        {[entry | data], new_ids, next_id + 1}
      end
  end)

Vl.new(width: 600, height: 300, title: "Compression Ratio vs Number of Merges")
|> Vl.data_from_values(Enum.reverse(ratio_data))
|> Vl.mark(:line, point: true)
|> Vl.encode_field(:x, "merges", type: :quantitative, title: "Number of Merges")
|> Vl.encode_field(:y, "ratio", type: :quantitative, title: "Compression Ratio (bytes / tokens)")
```

The steepest gains come from the first few merges — the most impactful patterns. Returns diminish as merges target rarer pairs.

## Encoding and Decoding

### Encoding: Apply Merges in Order

To encode new text, convert to bytes, then apply each merge rule left-to-right in the same order they were learned.

```elixir
encode = fn text, merges ->
  ids = :binary.bin_to_list(text)

  Enum.reduce(merges, ids, fn {{p1, p2}, new_id}, ids ->
    BPE.merge(ids, {p1, p2}, new_id)
  end)
end

encoded = encode.(training_text, merges)
IO.puts("Original: #{byte_size(training_text)} bytes")
IO.puts("Encoded:  #{length(encoded)} tokens")
```

### Decoding: Build the Vocabulary

Each merged token maps to the concatenation of its children's bytes.

```elixir
vocab = for i <- 0..255, into: %{}, do: {i, [i]}

vocab =
  Enum.reduce(merges, vocab, fn {{a, b}, id}, vocab ->
    bytes_a = Map.fetch!(vocab, a)
    bytes_b = Map.fetch!(vocab, b)
    Map.put(vocab, id, bytes_a ++ bytes_b)
  end)

decode = fn ids, vocab ->
  ids
  |> Enum.flat_map(&Map.fetch!(vocab, &1))
  |> :binary.list_to_bin()
end

IO.puts("Sample vocabulary entries:")

for {_pair, id} <- Enum.take(merges, 8) do
  bytes = Map.fetch!(vocab, id)
  text = :binary.list_to_bin(bytes)
  IO.puts("  token #{id} -> #{inspect(bytes)} -> #{inspect(text)}")
end
```

### Roundtrip: decode(encode(text)) == text

```elixir
test_texts = [
  "hello world",
  "the cat sat on the mat",
  training_text,
  "a brand new sentence that shares some words with the training data"
]

for text <- test_texts do
  tokens = encode.(text, merges)
  decoded = decode.(tokens, vocab)
  status = if decoded == text, do: "OK", else: "FAIL"
  ratio = Float.round(byte_size(text) / max(length(tokens), 1), 1)

  IO.puts(
    "#{status} #{byte_size(text)} bytes -> #{length(tokens)} tokens (#{ratio}x)" <>
      "  #{inspect(String.slice(text, 0, 50))}"
  )
end

IO.puts("\nBPE is lossless. Every byte sequence roundtrips perfectly.")
```

## Interactive: Type Text, Watch Tokenization

```elixir
text_input = Kino.Input.text("Type any text", default: "the cat sat on the mat")
```

```elixir
user_text = Kino.Input.read(text_input)
user_bytes = :binary.bin_to_list(user_text)
user_encoded = encode.(user_text, merges)

IO.puts("\"#{user_text}\"")
IO.puts("  Raw bytes: #{length(user_bytes)} tokens")
IO.puts("  After BPE: #{length(user_encoded)} tokens")
IO.puts("  Compression: #{Float.round(length(user_bytes) / max(length(user_encoded), 1), 2)}x")
IO.puts("\nTokens:")

for id <- user_encoded do
  text = :binary.list_to_bin(Map.fetch!(vocab, id))
  IO.puts("  #{String.pad_leading("#{id}", 4)}  #{inspect(text)}")
end
```

## Special Tokens

Real tokenizers need synthetic tokens for conversation structure — marking where user and assistant turns begin and end. These don't correspond to any byte sequence.

```elixir
special_tokens =
  ~w(<|bos|> <|user_start|> <|user_end|> <|assistant_start|> <|assistant_end|>
     <|python_start|> <|python_end|> <|output_start|> <|output_end|>)

special_start = 256 + length(merges)

special_map =
  special_tokens
  |> Enum.with_index(special_start)
  |> Map.new()

IO.puts("Vocabulary breakdown:")
IO.puts("  Base bytes:  0-255            (256 tokens)")
IO.puts("  Merges:      256-#{255 + length(merges)}          (#{length(merges)} tokens)")
IO.puts("  Special:     #{special_start}-#{special_start + length(special_tokens) - 1}          (#{length(special_tokens)} tokens)")
IO.puts("  Total:       #{special_start + length(special_tokens)} tokens")
```

## Break It

> **Predict**: Our BPE was trained on Shakespeare. What happens when we tokenize a word like "ChatGPT" that never appeared in the training corpus?

### Weird Splits: Why ChatGPT Tokenizes Words Strangely

BPE merges are learned from training data. This means tokenization depends on what patterns appeared in the corpus. Try encoding something that wasn't in the training data:

```elixir
for text <- ["the cat", "ChatGPT", "indivisible", "Elixir"] do
  tokens = encode.(text, merges)
  decoded_parts = Enum.map(tokens, fn id ->
    :binary.list_to_bin(Map.fetch!(vocab, id)) |> inspect()
  end)
  IO.puts("\"#{text}\" -> #{inspect(decoded_parts)}")
end

IO.puts("\nWords not in the training data get split into whatever subwords the")
IO.puts("tokenizer learned. This is why ChatGPT sometimes breaks words in")
IO.puts("unexpected places — it's the BPE merges from its training data.")
IO.puts("\nDifferent languages also tokenize differently. English words that")
IO.puts("were common in training get single tokens; rare scripts cost more.")
```

### Tiny Vocabulary (barely any merges)

```elixir
text = "the cat sat on the mat. the cat ate the rat."
full_encoded = encode.(text, merges)

ids = :binary.bin_to_list(text)
{tiny_merges, _, _} =
  Enum.reduce(1..2, {[], ids, 256}, fn _, {m, ids, nid} ->
    counts = count_pairs.(ids)
    if map_size(counts) == 0 do
      {m, ids, nid}
    else
      {best, _} = Enum.max_by(counts, fn {_, c} -> c end)
      {[{best, nid} | m], BPE.merge(ids, best, nid), nid + 1}
    end
  end)

tiny_encoded =
  Enum.reduce(Enum.reverse(tiny_merges), :binary.bin_to_list(text), fn {{p1, p2}, nid}, ids ->
    BPE.merge(ids, {p1, p2}, nid)
  end)

IO.puts("Tiny vocab  (258 tokens): #{length(tiny_encoded)} tokens for #{byte_size(text)} bytes")
IO.puts("Full vocab  (#{256 + length(merges)} tokens): #{length(full_encoded)} tokens for #{byte_size(text)} bytes")
IO.puts("\nWith almost no merges, no compression. Longer sequences = quadratically more attention compute.")
```

### Challenge: Train on Code vs English

What would BPE merges look like for Elixir source code vs English text? Think about it: code has `def`, `end`, `|>`, `fn`, `do` — completely different frequent pairs than English prose.

```elixir
english = "the cat sat on the mat. the cat ate the rat. the fat cat and the hat."

elixir_code = """
defmodule Foo do
  def bar(x) do
    x |> Enum.map(fn i -> i * 2 end) |> Enum.filter(fn i -> rem(i, 3) == 0 end)
  end
end
"""

for {name, text} <- [{"English", english}, {"Elixir", elixir_code}] do
  ids = :binary.bin_to_list(text)
  {top_merges, _, _} =
    Enum.reduce(1..10, {[], ids, 256}, fn _, {m, ids, nid} ->
      counts = count_pairs.(ids)
      if map_size(counts) == 0 do
        {m, ids, nid}
      else
        {best, freq} = Enum.max_by(counts, fn {_, c} -> c end)
        {[{best, freq} | m], BPE.merge(ids, best, nid), nid + 1}
      end
    end)

  IO.puts("#{name} — top 5 merges:")
  for {{a, b}, freq} <- Enum.take(Enum.reverse(top_merges), 5) do
    a_s = if a in 32..126, do: <<a>>, else: "#{a}"
    b_s = if b in 32..126, do: <<b>>, else: "#{b}"
    IO.puts("  '#{a_s}'+'#{b_s}'  x#{freq}")
  end
  IO.puts("")
end

IO.puts("Different corpora produce different merge tables.")
IO.puts("A tokenizer trained on English wastes tokens on code, and vice versa.")
IO.puts("This is why some models use separate tokenizers for code vs natural language.")
```

## Verify: Our BPE Matches the Library

```elixir
alias ExNanoGPT.V2.Tokenizer

tok = Tokenizer.train(training_text, vocab_size: 256 + num_merges + 9)

IO.puts("V2 Tokenizer: vocab_size=#{tok.vocab_size}, merges=#{length(tok.merges)}\n")

lib_ids = Tokenizer.encode(tok, training_text)
our_ids = encode.(training_text, merges)

IO.puts("Library encoding: #{length(lib_ids)} tokens")
IO.puts("Our encoding:     #{length(our_ids)} tokens")
IO.puts("Library roundtrip: #{Tokenizer.decode(tok, lib_ids) == training_text}")

IO.puts("\nFirst 5 merges — ours vs library:")

for i <- 0..min(4, length(merges) - 1) do
  ours = Enum.at(merges, i)
  lib = Enum.at(tok.merges, i)
  match = if ours == lib, do: "OK", else: "DIFF"
  IO.puts("  #{match} #{inspect(ours)}  vs  #{inspect(lib)}")
end

IO.puts("\nSame algorithm, same corpus, same merge count = identical results.")
```

## Real-World Connection

BPE is the reason ChatGPT sometimes splits words in unexpected ways. "indivisible" might become `["indiv", "isible"]` — not because it's buggy, but because those were the subword patterns learned from internet text.

It's also why different languages cost different numbers of tokens. English "hello" might be 1 token, but its equivalent in a less-represented language might be 3-5 tokens. This directly affects the cost and speed of using the API — you're billed per token.

The journey from a hobbyist compression algorithm in a 1994 C magazine to the foundation of trillion-dollar AI systems is one of the most remarkable stories in computer science.

## What's Next

We have a model and a tokenizer. But generating text is painfully slow — we're recomputing everything from scratch at every step. Next: **KV caching**, the optimization that was baked into the original Transformer from day one.

## Key Concepts

| Concept | What it means |
|---------|--------------|
| **Byte-Pair Encoding** | Iteratively merge the most frequent adjacent pair. Philip Gage, 1994. |
| **Subword tokenization** | BPE applied to NLP. Rico Sennrich et al., ACL 2016. |
| **Merge table** | Ordered list of (pair -> new_id) rules learned from training |
| **Encoding** | Convert text to bytes, apply merges left-to-right in order |
| **Decoding** | Map token IDs -> byte sequences -> UTF-8 string |
| **Special tokens** | Synthetic tokens for conversation structure (BOS, turn delimiters) |
| **Compression ratio** | bytes / tokens — higher means fewer tokens per character |
| **Corpus dependence** | Merges reflect training data; unseen patterns get poor compression |
